title: Aust bonds firmer after US jobs data
text:
Mon, Aug 10, 2015, 9:22 AM AEST - Australia Markets open in 38 mins. Aust bonds firmer after US jobs data AAP â€“ 16 minutes ago Print 
The Australian bond market is stronger as the chances of a US interest rate rise stay solid despite a weaker-than-expected jobs report for July. 
There were 215,000 jobs added to the US economy in July, which was below the gain of 229,000 economists had expected. 
The figures kept the US unemployment rate steady at a seven-year low of 5.3 per cent. 
St George senior economist Jo Horton said equities weakened following the jobs data but the futures market was pricing in an increased chance of a September rise in the Federal Funds Rate. 
"The monthly US payrolls report was close to economists expectations, but the market reaction was mixed," she said. 
"The Fed fund futures indicated investors are now pricing in 50 per cent chance of a rate hike from the Fed in September." 
At 0830 AEST on Monday, the September 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.215 (implying a yield of 2.785 per cent), up from 97.120 (2.880 per cent) on Friday. 
The September 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.050 (1.950 per cent), up from 98.010 (1.990 per cent). 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 1.947%, from 1.947% on Friday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 2.926%, from 2.926% 
Sydney Futures Exchange prices: 
* September 2015 bill futures, 97.870 from 97.880 
* December 2015 bill futures, 97.910, unchanged 
(*Closes taken at 1630 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
